- "Cumulative symptomatic cases" are the total number of reported symptomatic cases up to a certain point in time;
- "Tract" refers to a geographical area used for statistical purposes;
- "Influenza" is a specific disease excluded from the analysis.

- "tracts with a large population" refers to tracts with a population greater than 10,000;
- "highly transmissible diseases" refers to diseases with a transmission rate greater than 1.3;
- "total symptomatic cases" refers to the cumulative number of symptomatic cases reported up to the current time.

- "Tracts with a thriving population" refers to tracts with a population greater than 10,000;
- "During the first month" indicates the time points between 1 and 30;
- "Diseases with a fleeting incubation period" means diseases with an incubation period less than 7 days;
- "Symptoms were clearly visible" means the number of symptomatic cases reported is greater than 0.

- 'tracts' refers to geographic areas being monitored for disease cases;
- 'cumulative symptomatic cases' are the total number of reported symptomatic cases up to a certain point in time;
- 'population > 10000' filters tracts to only those with more than 10,000 residents.

- 'Growth rate' refers to the increase in the number of symptomatic cases over time;
- 'Average growth rate' is the mean of these growth rates calculated over multiple time points;
- 'Disease' is a condition that affects the health of individuals and can spread through populations;
- 'Symptomatic cases' are individuals who show signs or symptoms of the disease.

- "Most significant impact" refers to the diseases with the highest number of total cases;
- "Monitored by the health official" indicates that the data is specific to the reports created by a health official with a unique identifier (official_id = 1);
- "Monthly overview reports" are specific types of reports that cover a monthly data range.

- 'hotspots' refers to tracts with an average transmission rate greater than 1.0;
- 'like a wildfire' indicates a rapid spread of the disease;
- 'average count of those who have shown symptoms over time' refers to the average cumulative symptomatic cases.

- High transmission rate is considered to be greater than 0.5;
- The population threshold for the tracts is set to 10,000;
- "Highest number of cumulative symptomatic cases" refers to the top-ranked record for each tract.

- "affected" refers to the number of symptomatic cases;
- "above average" means the total number of symptomatic cases in a tract is greater than the average total symptomatic cases across all tracts;
- "population size" is the total number of people living in the tract;
- "cumulative number of symptomatic cases" is the total number of symptomatic cases reported up to the current time;
- "average transmission rate" is the mean estimated rate at which the disease spreads in the tract.

- "average cumulative wave of illness" refers to the average cumulative number of symptomatic cases;
- "surged beyond the general tide" means the average is higher than the overall average;
- "cresting height" refers to the average cumulative symptomatic cases;
- Disease ID 1 corresponds to COVID-19.

sql:
SELECT tract_name, population
FROM tracts
WHERE population > (SELECT AVG(population) FROM tracts);

